qualifies Agentic. 'Same across repeated calls' depends fundamentally on what the real model produces; keeping Agentic is required by the rejection gate.","test_description":"Call the real external AI API twice with an identical document and capture both returned labels. Assert the two labels are equal. Run this across a small sample of representative documents (3–5) to build statistical confidence that the determinism property holds, not just for one document by chance.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.15,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.75,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The number of tokens consumed for a typical document stays within the configured per-call budget.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is the module not enforcing the budget via the API request (e.g., not sending max_tokens or sending an incorrect value). This is a request-construction failure, parallel to Behavior 1. REAL-INFRA: No real HTTP or real LLM needed. A stub can capture the request and verify the token-budget parameter; a stub response can also carry a synthetic token-usage payload. MOCK-HIDE: If the module omits or misconfigures max_tokens, the outgoing request would expose this when captured by the stub. The API itself enforces completion token limits once max_tokens is set, so the real failure is in whether the module sends the correct parameter. LLM-DEP: Token consumption is bounded deterministically by max_tokens in the request; the actual completion content is irrelevant to whether the budget is respected. Prompt token count is also deterministic given a fixed document. INTEGRATION-BRAKE: (a) No real OS/network needed. (b) Correctness does not depend on AI output quality — it depends on the request parameter. (c) Not multi-step. REJECTION-GATE: Agentic would be needed only if we distrusted the API to enforce max_tokens, which is an unfounded assumption not supported by the behavior text.","test_description":"Set the module's token budget to a specific value (e.g., 200 tokens). Submit a representative document. Capture the outgoing API request with a stub client and assert max_tokens (or equivalent parameter) equals the configured budget. Also verify the module correctly reads and respects token-usage data from the stub response, rejecting any response whose reported total token count exceeds the budget.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.62,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.25,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the API signals that the request rate is too high, the module waits and retries rather than returning an error to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure is in how the module handles a 429 (or equivalent rate-limit) API response — a retry-logic failure that only appears when multiple modules interact (HTTP layer + retry/backoff logic + result return path). REAL-INFRA: A stub that returns 429 on the first call and 200 with a valid label on the second is sufficient to expose whether the module retries. Real network behavior is not needed; rate-limit responses are purely a matter of HTTP status codes. MOCK-HIDE: The stub's 429 directly exercises the failure path; a missing retry would surface immediately as an error returned to the caller. LLM-DEP: The behavior is about retry infrastructure — category (1) orchestration code — not about what the model decides. A deterministic stub is exactly right here. REJECTION-GATE: System would require real HTTP under real load; nothing in the behavior text requires that. Agentic would require real model output; this behavior is purely about error handling.","test_description":"Configure a stub HTTP server to return a 429 rate-limit response on the first request and a valid 200 classification response (with a label from the taxonomy) on the second. Mock or freeze the wait/sleep primitive so the test does not block. Call the module once and assert it returns a valid taxonomy label — not an exception or error — confirming that it retried transparently.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.12,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.03}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":12732,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":12732},"output_tokens":6,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4769e792-19f0-42d2-adcf-67bbac482638","uuid":"0cc9868d-af14-4958-ba06-f59ced2dc382"}
